Pitt brings Bard

By Jennifer Alpha
Staff Writer

Though the Three Rivers Shakespeare Festival will no
longer be spreading the works of the Bard to the Pittsburgh
community this summer, a piece of the festival still lives
on.

The Shakespeare in the Schools program, a surviving
unit of the festival, works to supplement the arts and cul-
tures curriculum in the region’s schools.

It “provides [schools] with something they couldn’t ordi-
narily do themselves,” said Bryn Jameson, artistic director
of Shakespeare in the Schools.

The Three Rivers Shakespeare Festival was canceled last
September when financial burdens and questions about the
direction of the festival made its continuance more of a
cost than a benefit. The Shakespeare in the Schools pro-
gram, however, was seen as an important vehicle for the
outreach of arts and culture, said Jameson. The program
was given a two-year test period to see how it develops
away from the structure of the festival.

This year’s tour is performing Shakespeare’s “Twelfth
Night,” a romantic comedy of love triangles and mistaken
identity. The tour, which started Jan. 23 and will travel to
parts of Pennsylvania, Ohio, Maryland and West Virginia

Resting on the lawn

until the end of April, presents an adapted version of the
piece to school children from grades kindergarten through
12.

The program’s main goal is to foster appreciation for
Shakespeare’s works.

“It gets kids to think differently about Shakespeare,”
Jameson said. “A lot of kids probably think it’s all just
doublets and swords.”

Though the play is shortened to 45 minutes, enough to fit
into one class period, Jameson stresses that the language
has been left unchanged.

“If you act it well, it should be understandable by any
age,” Jameson said. “I think it’s important to keep [the lan-
guage] pure, because that’s what makes Shakespeare spe-
cial.”

The production has a little help this year in catching the
children’s attention with a bright and colorful set and a
soundtrack by the Beatles.

When one of the chief characters, Malvolio, gets duped,
the Beatles’ lyrics “he’s a real nowhere man” sing
along.

Jameson said it seemed only right to have the sounds of a
revolutionary musical group fill the interludes of a work

