ThePitt News, Thursday, April 4, 1996

Summer language study available

By Rebecca Briggs
Copy Editor

While most students are lazing around
and enjoying the warm weather this sum-
mer, 50 to 60 of them will be participating
in Pitt’s Russian and East European
Summer Language Intensives.

This program, which will celebrate its
10th anniversary this year, provides partic-
ipating students with beginning courses in
nine languages. More advanced students
may also take intermediate Slovak, Polish
and Serbian, as well as up to fourth-year
Russian.

The six-week East European language
courses run from June 24 until August 2,
while the Russian courses last eight
weeks, from June 10 until August 10.

The focus of the program is oral profi-
ciency, or “accelerated intensiveexposure
to the language,” according to its coordi-
nator, John Kachur. Students work on their
grammar, reading and listening compre-
hension skills for five hours a day in class
and eat and converse together at lunch.
They may also participate in a variety of
extracurricular activities such as the chess
club, the cooking club, receptions and
films, all of which are geared to foster fur-
ther cultural exposure.

“You come here as a total beginner and
get a very good background in the lan-

guage,” said Kachur.

Although most students are from the
Pittsburgh area, some come from other
parts of the country. Not all participants
are traditional students. Some are older
adults who wish to brush up on their lan-
guage skills before traveling to Eastern
Europe. According to Kachur, the program
has proved useful in the past to missionar-
ies hoping to spread their message in the
region.

“It is a wonderful way to get exposure
and get ahead in language training without
the distraction of the regular school year,”
said Kachur. “[It provides] a good prepa-
ration for going abroad.”

All students, whether from Pennsylvania
or out-of—state, pay in-state-tuition for the
credits, plus programs fees. Scholarships
for the undergraduate program are avail-
able and are based upon academic merit as
well as financial need. The deadline for
these scholarships is April. 10.
Applications for admission will be accept-
ed until the program starts.

Graduate students may apply for the
Foreign Language Area Stipend, which
provides full tuition as well as a stipend.

For more information about the program
or scholarships, call Kachur or Dova
Wilson at 624-5906, or visit the Slavic

' Department’s office in Room 1417 of the

Cathedral of Learning.

 

