Open street brawling

If you have all the answers, don’t ask any questions.

That message is for City Council President Jim Ferlo. Why did
you waste everyone’s time Tuesday night by holding a public hear-
ing on the proposed Bigelow Boulevard closing when you already
knew that you were going to vote against it?

Pitt students (well, around 50 of them), finally shed their apathet-
ic skin and showed up at the hearing. They want Bigelow closed,
and some of them spoke for the closing.

Interim Chancellor Mark Nordenberg spoke, as did Vice-
Chancellor for Student and Public Affairs Leon Haley. They also
tried to convince the council to vote for the closing, as did the city
planning director, the parking director and other Pitt and city offi-
cials.

Ferlo sat back in his chair and took it all in. But it was clear from
his attitude towards the pro-closure speakers where his opinion lay.
At one point, he asked the city planning director, “Do you have any
other tests, bogus or otherwise?”

Sure, it was only a joke and brought some laughter from the
crowd, but this wasn’t the Funnybone. It was a public hearing,
where at least in principle, the voters have a chance to change
things.

That’s right, Jim. Change things. And if you’re not careful about
how you deal with Pitt, the largest constituency you have, then
maybe the City Council president will change names.

Light ‘em up and sue

Here’s a news ﬂash: Nicotine is addictive. In case any of you
have never smoked or never known a smoker at some point in your
life, 60 law firms are making it their business to make sure every-
one knows it and gets paid for knowing it.

A class action suit is currently in progress, in which 60 firms
across the country are lining up litigants to sue tobacco companies
for concealing the fact that nicotine is addictive and for adding
nicotine to cigarettes to keep all the smokers smoking.

The question is, does anyone out there deny that smoking is

- addictive? The tobacco companies deny that they hid that fact

(which they couldn’t have) and that they manipulated tobacco lev-
els (which remains to be seen). However, the more important ques-
tion is, exactly what do the lawyers hope to gain by filing this suit?

The only possible answer is money.

A huge contingency fee lurks in the comers if lawyers success-
fully sue the tobacco companies. Anyone named as a claimant in
the class action will be financially rewarded for having a bad habit.

If tobacco companies lied, they should be fined -— heavily —— by
the groups that govern the rules of business and sales. But even if
people “knew” (officially, that is) that nicotine was addictive, there
would still be cigarette companies and there will always be smok-
ers.

So smoke ‘em if you got ‘em, then call the lawyer nearest you.

