This Monday, April 8, at 8
p.m., locals Blunderbuss, ska
giants The Stubborn All-Stars
and Chicago's own decon-
structionist writer/ranter
Wesley Willis and his Fiasco
will appear at Luciano's. This
is a show unlike any other. It's
all there, except for the steel
cage.

Blunderbuss provides the
indie component of the show.
playing their native blend of
noisy heavy, hard-hitting, gui-
tar rock. They'll be showcas-

ing new material written since
their last release Conspiracy
(Homestead Records). If you
like a little noise with your cof-
fee, this is for you.

The Stubborn All—Stars are
the grizzled veterans of the
ska world, having played in
famous bands like The
Toasters, among others, for
years. These guys were play-
ing way back before you even
came to college and found
out those checkered skin-
heads weren't Nazis. To use

the obligatory ska pun, they're
not Skahnny-come-latelies.
Hell, you might even hear
some classic Jamaican—style
riffs before the night is out.
Lastly, Wesley Willis returns
to Pittsburgh with his pop~cul-
ture references and righteous
raves. Wesley really is a men-
tal patient in every sense of
the word (we‘re talking med-
ication here), but his observa-
tions on life, delivered over a
heavy punk musical back-
drop. aren‘t to be missed.

Skip the bootleg tapes and
see him live.

Finally, for all you egghead,
bookworm, artistic types out
there, Daniel Morrow will give
a performance reading of his
work Ondine. Featuring musi-
cians and theatrical elements.
Morrow‘s reading will elabo-
rate on his book about the
Warhol film superstar. It all
takes place at Borders in the
South Hills on Saturday, April
6.

——sean stevens

 
  
 

 

 

