l’ve spent the last day and a
half listening to the new
Cracker album, The Golden
Age, and upon first impres-
sion, Cracker appears to be
backsiiding. David Lowry has
gotten too caught up in trying
to be a “Great Experimenter of
Rock ‘n’ Roll” and has forgot-
ten that Cracker was a band
that was born to express the
guts and intensity of the very
talented core of musicians that
came together for the music.

This album, in contrast to
Cracker's last effort, Kerosene
Hat, is over-produced, over-
complicated with unnecessary
instrumentation and a bit weak
in the conviction department.
When he fronted the avante-
folk outfit, Camper Van
Beethoven, Lowry was fighting
to play folk rock in an era
where synth pop and New
Wave were the rule of the day.
Lowry left Camper Van
Beethoven to form Cracker, a
much tighter, stripped-down
rock outfit that kicked ass and
took names in a way that the
lighter, less gutsy Camper Van
Beethoven never could.
Cracker’s first album was a
reasonable market success,
driven by the force of the
“Teen Angst (What the world
needs now)” single that took
college radio by storm. Lowry,
a college radio fave for years,
finally found a voice in which
to speak to larger audiences in
the form of Cracker.

Two of the biggest reasons
for that success were the
amazingly talented and soulful
Johnny Hickman on lead gui-
tar and bassist extrordinaire,
Davey Faragher. Hickman’s
Neil Young-meets-Led
Zeppelin guitar lines created
an energy that, woven into the
tapestry of Lowry’s simple and
catchy melodies, took the folk-
rock genre to a new level.
Faragher’s stripped-down,
funky bass style was an
unlikely, but somehow perfect-
ly suited, match for the
Hickman/Lowry team. Songs
like “This is Cracker Soul” and
“Get off of This” owe their ton-
of-bricks groove to Faragher’s
basslines as much, or more,
than anything else. And it was
Faragher’s ability to create
space, to know when not to
play, and to somehow express
that intangible essence of soul
into even the simplest and
slowest of songs, that helped
create the well-rounded sound
of Cracker. Now, Faragher is
gone and his absence is
incredibly conspicuous on The

 

 

  

Golden Age.

lt’s not that this is a bad
album by any means. It just
does not measure up to the
standard set by Kerosene Hat.
Granted, Lowry set the bar
pretty high for his band, but
somewhere along the way the
soul got lost, or at least dis-
tilled. Somehow, some of the
chemistry went with Faragher.
Bob Fiupe proves to be a com-
petent bassist but hardly wor-
thy of filling Faragher’s shoes.
Faragher just had that special,
intangible and oh-so-rare qual-
ity of soul that can't be
defined, bought, taught, pack-
aged or replaced. Even rarer
was Faragher’s ability to go
into the studio and make that
soul stick to tape. So, in his
absence, Lowry and Hickman
went in search of new fron-
tiers. What they came up with
was an album that tries to
compensate for a drop in the
quality of songwriting and
band unity by overburdening
tracks with endless piano,
steel guitar, keyboard, backing
vocal and string tracks. Lowry
and Co. never skated the line
of Glam rock enough to pull off
a fully orchestrated string
arrangement, and it shows. in
a quest to. be “experimental,”
Lowry and co-producer David
Herring have taken away
Cracker’s anchor of simplicity
and allowed this album to be
washed away in the-tides of
self-indulgence and overpro-
duction.

There are some good
moments. The single for ‘‘I
Hate My Generation” is getting
a lot of commercial airplay and
certainly rocks a lot harder
than most of the candy-pop
grunge bands that are current-
ly littering this nation's so-
called “Alternative” and “New
Rock” airwaves. David Lowry
can still craft a song better
than most guys out there.
Johnny Hickman is one of the
best rock guitarists out there
and he pulls some solos on
this album that leave my jaw
hanging open at the beautifully
simple yet elegant phrasing
that he manages to eke out of
his old Les Paul Eldorado.

Guest appearances by the
likes of Tony Maimone (bass),
David lmmergluck (pedal
steel) and Joan Osborne
(backing vocals) are certainly
nice, and it's good to see a lit-
tle old fashioned music indus-
try nepotism at work, but
there’s just no reason for it all.
lt’s too much. It just seems like
Cracker is trying so hard not to
be pigeonholed by MTV and
commercial radio that they are
caving into the very pressures
they set out to avoid. To make
a conscious effort to make an
album that is markedly differ-
ent from previous material is,

April 4 1 996

in this case at least, just one
expression of the self-con-
sciousness that major label
fame and PR hype can create.
The success of the last album
also gave the band a chance
to rest on their laurels and
plan their next move a bit too
thoroughly. By trying to avoid
expectations, Cracker has
backed themselves into a cre-
ative corner of their own con-
coction. And that’s a mouthful.
Bottom line: There are a lot of
good ideas on this album, but
few good songs. The loss of
Faragher set Cracker back
tremendously. Hopefully this
album will put Cracker’s back
to the wall. it seems to be
where they thrive.

——joel lederer
