Pellegrini’s production of Luigi
Pirandello’s Futurist play,
Enrico IV. Pirandello contem-
plates madness and all of its
ancillaries, delving into the
meaning of language and its
epistemological bounds
through a Foucalt-like exami-
nation of life and how time's
permanent and indefinite
nature can create labels like
“madman” and “imbecile.”

The show opens with a blar-
ing statement of intent by a
Futurist (Aaron Christian
Harms) and an audio-visual
montage of Squonk Opera-like
movements and sounds that
incorporated an ensemble of
Futurists (Harms, Daniel
Massaro, Bob Reufle,
Dawnelle Stutzman, Tim
Golebiewski and Rachel Wynn)
introducing the Futurist artistic
mission of change and forward

movement in expression.

The story of Enrico IV is as
convoluted as the many ideas
that Pirandello explores; Enrico
IV (Kevin J. Wetmore) is simply
“mad.” After falling from a
horse while riding in a historical
pageant, he believes himself to
be an 11th-century German
emperor excommunicated by
the Pope. This being estab-
lished, the show is then a com-
plex array of analyses of
Enrico’s psychology through
philosophical discussions with
his servants (Howard Williams,
Jr., Joe Manganiello, Tim
Wisniewski, Dennis Pennell)
and different people trying to
understand him, like the metic-
