ever—changing world of college tennis.

Consider this: NCAA tennis coaches stay at one school
an average of 3.5 years. Dieffenbach, 42, has exceeded
the average more than five times over.

Explaining his longevity, Dieffenbach said, “The num-
bers tell it all.” It’s typical Dieffenbach, letting actions -
and records — speak louder than words.

With Dieffenbach courtside, the men’s and women’s
tennis teams have posted a combined record of 312-261.

During those matches, he is a relatively quiet observer,
occasionally shouting encouragement or a suggestion to
one of his players. Yet he sees, and remembers, every lit-
tle hitch.

As a player, Dieffenbach was 32-13, good for 13th on
the all-time win list at Pitt.

Dieffenbach, a member of Shadyside Presbyterian
Church and a Sunday school teacher there, admires those
with a Puritan-like work ethic. He names Bjorn Borg as
his all-time favorite tennis star because, according to him,
Borg was a “quiet fighter.”

Dieffenbach attributes his success to hard work and his
20 years at one school — especially his 20 years at one
school.

